  "final_answer": "Yes—there are coastal tracts with relatively low prices, using a low-price cutoff of about \\textbf{$162.5k} for coastal areas.\n\nOverall, coastal homes are usually expensive:\n- <1H OCEAN: median about $213.6k\n- NEAR BAY: median about $231.9k\n- NEAR OCEAN: median about $235.1k\n\nBut some coastal locations fall far below that, with examples as low as:\n- <1H OCEAN at (-118.33, 34.15): about $17.5k\n- NEAR BAY at (-122.32, 37.93): about $22.5k\n- NEAR OCEAN at (-120.59, 34.70): about $28.3k\n\nThe clearest pattern is that cheaper coastal areas tend to have weaker socioeconomic and housing-quality indicators than coastal areas overall:\n- \\textbf{Lower income}: median income averages 2.66 in low-price coastal tracts vs 4.17 overall\n- Smaller homes / less space: rooms per household are 4.46 vs 5.17\n- More crowding: population per household is 3.38 vs 2.93\n- Higher bedroom share: bedrooms per room are 0.248 vs 0.218, consistent with tighter housing layouts\n- Slightly older housing on average: 32.2 years vs 30.7\n\nSo the most likely explanation is that proximity to the ocean alone does not guarantee high prices. Coastal areas can still be relatively cheap when they have \\textbf{lower local incomes, more crowded housing, fewer/lower-quality rooms, and in some cases older housing stock}.",
